      "title": "City of Evil in The Rev's Discography and A7X Drummer History",
      "content": "*City of Evil* sits at the center of The Rev's creative arc. It is the album where his technical drumming reached mainstream audiences for the first time at scale — the record that, for most listeners, answered the question \"What is The Rev actually capable of?\" — and it remains the primary document of his artistry for anyone encountering A7X's music for the first time.\n\n**The Pre-City of Evil Era:**\nThe Rev recorded *Sounding the Seventh Trumpet* (2001) and *Waking the Fallen* (2003) with A7X in the metalcore underground. Those records established the foundation of his vocabulary — jazz-influenced fills within extreme metal structures, unconventional accent placements, melodic tom patterns — but reached relatively limited commercial audiences. *Waking the Fallen* in particular is considered by many fans to contain his most technically aggressive drumming, before *City of Evil* redirected that energy toward more hook-driven arrangements.\n\n**The City of Evil Era (2005):**\n*City of Evil* made The Rev visible to the mainstream heavy metal audience. The Pearl Masters MCX and Zildjian A Custom combination — his gear identity for this period — became associated with his name in the public consciousness. The Grammy nomination for \"Beast and the Harlot\" brought institutional recognition. He toured *City of Evil* extensively through 2005–2006, establishing himself as a live performer at arena scale.\n\n**The Later Albums:**\nThe self-titled *Avenged Sevenfold* (2007) continued the same gear platform (MCX kit, A Custom cymbals) with a more elaborate production context. By 2009, The Rev had begun composing drum parts for what would become *Nightmare* — the album that was completed posthumously with Mike Portnoy performing his compositions as a tribute. For the Nightmare story, see [Nightmare drum setup (Mike Portnoy, 2010)](/articles/nightmare-drum-setup).\n\n**The Legacy:**\nThe Rev died on December 28, 2009, at age 28. His death generated immediate and sustained cultural attention — obituary-adjacent queries about his discography, his gear, and the band he helped found remain among the highest-traffic searches in the A7X/metal drummer space years later. *City of Evil* is the primary answer to \"What did The Rev actually play on?\" — the album where his artistry is most accessibly documented.",
